description: Jennie Galbraith, head of environment, social and governance (ESG) at BAT, talks to Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, about all aspects of ESG in her role ‚Äì from providing insights and tracking developments in the external environment, and working with the business to ensure it becomes more sustainable by understanding the true nature of impacts on nature and society, to managing ESG reporting and engagement with investors.
title: Leading The Corporate ESG Agenda With Jennie Galbraith, Head Of ESG, BAT

description:
While financial reporting standards develop in a more or less coherent way between jurisdictions, it is far from clear that the same will be true of ESG disclosure standards. Although companies are required to report on the broader impact of their business, there are no clearly defined standards for doing so, and the level of audit assurance is typically lower.

Governments, however, increasingly recognise that the role of the private sector in getting to net-zero can only be properly evaluated if there is a more standardised approach to non-financial reporting. Moves towards more structured disclosure around people, the planet and purpose could, however, bring materiality risks.

How do you manage all this if you are sitting in a corporate? Does it have to create an army of metrics trackers and verifiers? How do you ensure compliance across different countries and through your supply chain? Will those countries get together to create common reporting standards?

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were delighted to be joined by Nick Pennell, Group Programme Director at Essentra, and Hannah Kendrick, partner in our Corporate Practice.
title: Risks Of Non-Financial Disclosure Requirements (23 June 2021)

description:
Fifteen years ago, Clive Humby famously said, ‚Äúdata is the new oil.‚Äù But do we really understand how data, the ability to collect and analyse it, and the extent to which an organisation is capable of assimilating technological innovation are drivers of value? What makes a ‚Äúsmart‚Äù company? Does being ‚Äúsmart‚Äù necessarily deliver greater value? Or do you have to be smart about how you are ‚Äúsmart‚Äù?

Is technology no longer just for techies?

Guest Speakers -

¬∑         Hugh Campbell, Founder, GP Bullhound
¬∑         Pinesh Mehta, Investor, BGF
¬∑         Carlton Daniel, Partner, Intellectual Property & Technology

Tony Reed, EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, provides an introduction and Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, hosts the discussion.
title: Driving Value - Data, Technology And IP (13 May 2021)

description:
With the end to restrictions in sight, some businesses are preparing for the return to the office while others have moved to hybrid or fully agile models. We explore the considerations of a full or partial return for teams, as well as the evolving landscape for occupiers.

We hear from Nationwide on its approach to allow over 70% of its staff to choose where they want to work from under its new hybrid working model; and discuss the impacts for property owners and investors as some businesses look more favourably at a flexible space over the traditional tenant model.

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we are delighted to be joined by James Rowlands, Lead Policy & Public Affairs Manager at Nationwide; Carl Potter, Managing Director at Avison Young Birmingham; and Caroline Noblet, co-chair of our Labour & Employment Practice.
title: The Future Workplace (28 April 2021)

description:
International affairs advisor Matthew Kirk discusses with our panellists the importance of the partnership between governments and the private sector to provide the necessary infrastructure, incentives and consumer education, in conjunction with affordable products, that will make it possible for challenging climate change and green transport targets to be met in the US, the UK and the EU.

‚ÄúWithout leadership, nothing is possible. With leadership, everything is possible.‚Äù Secretary Slater

Panellists:

- Rodney Slater, Partner, Squire Patton Boggs, and Former US Secretary of Transportation
- Mike Hawes, Chief Executive, Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders
- Fiona Howarth, Chief Executive, Octopus EV
title: Powering The Drive Towards Net Zero (15 April 2021)

description:
Attention on corporate purpose is beginning to shift from a focus on financial results, responsible investing and climate-related financial disclosures to corporate behaviour, with greater transparency of ESG issues, including contributions towards fulfilled societies and a sustainable approach to the planet.

With the recently released World Economic Forum common metrics for sustainable value creation, is potential mandatory reporting on your agenda? Join us for this event, where we will be exploring the consequences of poor governance and transparency, whether future dividend payments and compensation packages will be tied to climate-related measures, and what steps you should be taking to protect your company from litigation and preserve your reputation.

Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, was joined by Sacha Sadan, Director of Investment Stewardship, LGIM, Andrew Lin, Head of Project Finance and Infrastructure group at DBRS Morningstar and Louise Barber, director in our Corporate Practice.
title: Corporate Reporting On Sustainable Value Creation (24 March 2021)

description:
International M&A practitioners are used to dealing with CFIUS for any transaction involving assets in the US. The Europeans M&A practitioners are, however, catching up, and many multijurisdictional deals will now face clearance in a number of countries. The latest addition to the list, the UK National Security and Investment Bill, is broad in scope and potentially far-reaching in coverage. Deals now potentially face multiple levels of scrutiny, each with its own scope, trigger criteria, potential remedies, etc., and the scrutiny is likely to be more subjective and less predictable than practitioners are used to with merger clearance.

To help navigate this complex landscape, we discussed the different regimes in place over key jurisdictions.

The following panellists discussed the relevant rules:
¬∑         George Grammas, partner, International Trade, Washington DC
¬∑         Oliver Geiss, partner, Competition ‚Äì Antitrust, Brussels
¬∑         Francesco Liberatore, partner, Competition ‚Äì Antitrust, London
¬∑         Diarmuid Ryan, partner, Competition ‚Äì Antitrust, London
¬∑         Tony Reed, EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, Paris
¬∑         Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, London
title: Multi-Country M&A Is Getting More Complex - Evolving FDI Regimes UK, Europe and US (18 March 2021)

description: In this episode, senior tax policy advisor Robert O‚ÄôHare (London) discusses the current state of UK tax policy relating to cross-border trade and investment, including the measures announced in the Chancellor‚Äôs 2021-22 Budget speech.
title: International Tax Policy - UK Tax Policy Developments And Outlook

description: In this episode, public policy advisor Christina Economides (Brussels) discusses current EU proposals related to taxation, including public country-by-country reporting, the digital levy, the Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism and the revision of the Energy Taxation Directive.
title: International Tax Policy - EU Tax Policy Developments And Outlook

description: In this episode, partner Jeff VanderWolk and associate Rory Murphy (Washington DC) discuss the OECD/G20 Inclusive Framework‚Äôs project on the tax challenges of digitalization, including its implications for US trade policy with respect to digital services taxes in Europe and elsewhere. The status of both Pillar One, on nexus and profit allocation, and Pillar Two, on the GloBE minimum tax regime, will be covered.
title: International Tax Policy - The Inclusive Framework Process, With Trade Law Ramifications

description:
Tariff free and quota free sounds great, but companies are already finding that it is not as simple as that. Some are encountering significant complexity in customs clearances and border procedures and while these will add to the complexity and cost of trade in the future, we would expect these process issues to calm down over time.

More serious for the long term is the impact of the rules of origin regime. This is not something that companies can navigate their way round, or learn, as with customs processes. If the effect of rules of origin through your supply chain is that your product attracts tariffs, you will either have to pay the tariffs or change your supply chain. This is particularly the case for supply chains that cross the EU-UK border during the production process ‚Äì the fact that you have sourced your components or ingredients into the UK from inside the EU does not mean that they necessarily count as EU origin when the rules are applied to their re-export back to the EU.

In this podcast we discuss Rules of Origin, the impacts on the manufacturing sector (including food and drink and consumer product manufacturing) and what your longer-term strategy may need to involve.

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Fergus McReynolds, Director of EU Affairs at MAKE UK and Robert Maclean, partner in our International Trade team.
title: Navigating Rules Of Origin (24 February 2021)

description:
Data security breaches remain a key source of concern for most businesses. In this discussion, our panel of experts provide valuable insights from their experiences of handling and reporting data security breaches during the last year. Rosa Barcelo, co-chair of our Data Privacy & Cybersecurity (DPC) Practice, and Francesca Fellowes, director in our DPC Practice, report on developments in this area during the course of 2020. This includes looking at how different types of data breach reports are being handled by the supervisory authorities in both the UK and the EU, as well as the mitigating factors they focus on in deciding whether to take enforcement action, drawing on both practical experience and the recent EDPB Guidelines 01/2021 on Examples regarding Data Breach Notification.

We also examine the recent increase in ‚Äúno win, no fee‚Äù data breach claims in the UK following a data breach report made to affected individuals, drawing upon the experience of Victoria Leigh, partner in our Litigation Practice, in dealing with these claims. In light of the increased risk of data breach claims, getting the content of a data breach notification to affected individuals right has never been more important. Our panel were be joined by Tim Luckett, Global Crisis Lead at Hill+Knowlton Strategies, who provides us with the benefit of his considerable expertise in handling data breach communications.

Tony Reed, EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduced the speakers and Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, hosted the discussion.
title: Data Security Breaches ‚Äì Mitigating Risk & Why It Can Cost Much More Than A Fine (18 February 2021)

description:
As we confront Lockdown 3.0 and the vaccination rollout, employers face workforce decisions without precedent or a legislative background designed for these circumstances.

In this podcast you‚Äôll hear perspectives on balancing the medical and ethical choices surrounding vaccinations, and whether businesses can implement return-to-office policies only for those that have chosen to be vaccinated. These choices may be economically sensible and lawful, but how do you protect your reputation and the internal and external perception of your business while navigating these decisions? What is the best way forward? What are other countries doing? How should employers plan in this vaccination phase to ensure they protect their workforce and avoid future legal challenges?

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Professor Jeffrey Almond, director and scientific advisor to several biotech companies in Europe, the UK and the US. He is a visiting professor at a number of universities and previously Vice President of Research and External R&D at Sanofi Pasteur. They were joined by Caroline Noblet , co-chair of our Labour & Employment Practice.
title: Vaccination Rollout And The Workplace; Ethical And Legal Considerations (27 January 2021)

description:
With heightened public awareness around single-use plastics, and ever-evolving sustainability and circular economy policies, many boardrooms across Europe and beyond have been placing these issues high on their agendas. In addition, there are significant changes ahead for the plastics producing, recycling and using industries in 2021.

Gloria Gabellini, director of Environmental Policy at PepsiCo, and Jens Kathmann, secretary general at Styrenics Circular Solutions, were joined by our own experts Anita Lloyd, director, and Ken Huestebeck, senior associate, to explore some of the forthcoming regulatory policy proposals on plastics recycling in the EU and the UK that will impact businesses.  The discussion looked at the objectives policy-makers are trying to achieve and public support for them, current regulatory obligations and the challenges of adapting to meet them, new mechanisms such as plastics taxes, the importance of re-cycling, and future directions in regulatory and industry-led initiatives.  The discussion also highlighted a feature of Brexit ‚Äì the EU and the UK trying to achieve very similar objectives, but choosing different means to do so.

Tony Reed, EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduced the speakers and Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, led the discussion.
title: Future of Plastics (14 January 2021)

description: In the first of our Taking the Lead podcast series, Rajiv Sharma, group chief executive of Coats, talks to Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, about leading the business through the COVID-19 pandemic. He explores the steps taken by the company this year to support its employees, their families and local communities; how it overcame the technological challenges of communicating in a time of crisis; the importance of a robust risk management and governance framework in maintaining business continuity; and the impact of the company‚Äôs culture and values on employee engagement during difficult times.
title: Leading a Business Through a Pandemic With Rajiv Sharma, CEO of Coats

description:
Matthew Kirk in Conversation With Paul Adamson

Paul Adamson is chairman of Forum Europe, editor of the online magazine Encompass and founder of the EU-UK Forum. He has been a prominent member of the Brussels policy community in a variety of guises for most of the UK‚Äôs period of membership of the EU.

Matthew Kirk is our international affairs advisor. He is a former British Ambassador and former Vodafone Executive, and has been active in European policy for more than 30 years.
title: Brexit Stocktake - Where Are We? How Did We Get Here? What Happens Next? (14 December 2020)

description:
In this discussion we looked back at 2020, a year like no other, and looked ahead to 2021. Matthew Kirk, International Affairs Advisor, was joined by the co-founders of EOS Deal Advisory, Ina Kjaer and Maggie Brereton, who shared insights and views on everything from the COVID-19 crisis to the US elections, Brexit and the EU budget, as well as the impact of all these epic issues on dealmaking. With their ‚ÄúEyes Wide Open‚Äù approach to advising on deals, they took a look into next year and offered their perspective on some of the key trends and factors that will be instrumental in determining whether future value is to be delivered once the deals have been done.

Tony Reed EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduced the speakers and Matthew Kirk hosted the discussion.
title: A Year Like No Other ‚Äì Looking Back At 2020 ‚Äì And Looking Ahead To 2021 (10 December 2020)

description:
The European Commission recently published the long-awaited new (draft) standard contractual clauses (SCCs) for transfers of personal data outside the EEA. These are open for consultation, but once approved, organisations will have a one-year grace period to implement the new SCCs, if they rely on them for transfers. The new SCCs update the current clauses, which were not amended for the GDPR, and will allow for a range of transfer scenarios (including those between processors and from processors to controllers) and importer/exporters in and outside of the EEA. However, with so much going on ‚Äì with the end of the Brexit transition period (with no deal as yet between the UK and the EU) and the need to assess transfers and SCCs following Schrems II, combined with the possible impact of the recent CJEU Judgement on UK mass surveillance powers, when is the right time to update them?

Listen to our Data Privacy & Cybersecurity Practice discuss what the new SCCs look like, what businesses should be prioritising now, whether ‚Äúquick fixes‚Äù can be adopted and what you need to be aware of.

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Andrea Ward, director in our Data Privacy and Cybersecurity Practice and Kate Lewis, Data Protection Officer, GB Group.
title: Standard Contractual Clauses For Data Transfers ‚Äì Is Now The Right Time? (2 December 2020)

description:

Soren gave his practical insight on the impact of these changes in a period of rapid expansion and recruitment for TikTok in the UK and the EU. 

Tony Reed, EMEA Chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduced the discussion and Matthew Kirk, was the host.
title: The Impact Of Brexit On Business Travel And Immigration Between The UK And The EU (26 November 2020)

description:
As the country is now in a second lockdown at one of the busiest trading periods of the year, many sectors will be facing a difficult Christmas period. The challenges to the retail and hospitality sector will be felt more keenly than most. However, there are investors for whom troubled sectors are still an interesting proposition.

We heard perspectives on the state-of-play within the sector, to what extent the government‚Äôs support continues to address the challenges within it and why private capital is stepping up to help the economic recovery. As we move into 2021, how will the sector fare and how might that government support evolve?

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Tom Jack, partner at Endless LLP, Richard Lim, chief executive of Retail Economics and Prew Lumley, partner in our Real Estate Practice.
title: Is Private Capital The Answer For The Retail Sector? (18 November 2020)

description:
For years, boards have grappled with how to address very low probability, very high impact risk scenarios. A simple arithmetical extraction from a risk matrix can leave the impression of overspending on a remote contingency when it does not materialize, and woeful lack of preparation and mitigation when it does. The effect of the COVID-19 pandemic on business has underlined this acute dichotomy ‚Äì some businesses had a reference to pandemics in their risk register, others did not, but could point to vaguer formulations, which gave them some declaratory cover. How many businesses had genuinely prepared for a once-in-a-century disruption on the scale we have seen?

Looking forward, how should boards and executive teams think about external risk? Can arithmetical extrapolations of probability against impact be used to allocate resource to mitigating risk? In the UK, the FRC‚Äôs Governance Code requires a robust assessment of the company‚Äôs principal risks. However, how can a board assess the risk that an extraneous event will cause the government to shut down large parts of the economy? How useful is the concept of risk appetite for assessing macro risks? Should a company‚Äôs risk register focus on the risks for which the company can effectively mitigate the impact or affect the incidence? How useful in assessing a company as a going concern are references in risk registers to pandemics, elections, etc.?

Tony Reed, EMEA Chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduced the speakers and Matthew Kirk, International Affairs Advisor, hosted the discussion. 

Our panelists were:
¬∑         Nell Cady-Kruse, Non-executive Director, Barclays US LLC and Barclays Bank Delaware
¬∑         Thomas Tyler, Global Head of Sales, ELITE, London Stock Exchange
¬∑         Louise Barber, Legal Director, Squire Patton Boggs
title: Boardroom Dilemmas - Navigating Corporate Risk In Uncertain Times (3 November 2020)

description:
This edition of the podcast provides an update on the US elections from Jeff Turner. Jeff works with domestic and international clients to advance their business objectives on Capitol Hill and in the executive branch. Collaborating with colleagues in the Public Policy Practice Group, he and his teams help block harmful legislation and regulations, encourage Congress and regulatory agencies to adopt favorable legislation and regulations, and navigate the challenges of congressional investigations.

Tony Reed, EMEA Chair of the global Corporate Practice, provided the introductions, and Matthew Kirk, International Affairs Advisor, hosted the discussion.
title: Post-US Elections Update (12 November 2020)

description:
The impact that COVID-19 has had on companies is huge. Many have faced, and will continue to face, the toughest of decisions concerning their staff (redundancies, unpaid leave, pay cuts, etc.) without either any real support by way of precedent or a legislative background designed for these circumstances.

In this podcast we hear perspectives on balancing the needs of the business with workforce decisions. These choices may be economically sensible and lawful, but how do you protect your reputation and internal and external perception of your business while navigating these decisions? What is the best way forward? What are other people doing? We have insights on how some companies have achieved this and, in particular, how they are seeking to balance the human and financial aspects of the many crossroads that now confront them.

Hosted by international affairs advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Iain Burton, CEO, Aspinal of London, David Whincup, head of our Labour & Employment Practice in London, and Paula Laird, partner in our Financial Services Practice, who has been guiding clients through pre-packs and CVAs during the pandemic.
title: Hard Decisions In Hard Times (4 November 2020)

description:
The range of possible outcomes on data transfers between the EU and the UK could lead to major changes and considerable complexity. For any company doing business across the Brexit border, even if both parties want to make it easy, there may be significant impacts post-Brexit.

This podcast explores the range of possible outcomes, the constraints that make obvious solutions harder ‚Äì including the potential effect of two key ECJ judgements this year, and how companies need to prepare.

Hosted by International Affairs Advisor Matthew Kirk, we were joined by Neil Ross, Policy Manager for Digital Economy at techUK and Rosa Barcelo, Co-Chair of our global Data Privacy & Cybersecurity Practice and former Deputy Head of Unit of the Cybersecurity and Digital Privacy Unit of DG CONNECT in the European Commission.
title: Why Data May Prove One Of The Hardest Parts Of Brexit (21 October 2020)

description:
Hear from US Representative Joe Crowley and US Representative Jack Kingston during the final weeks of the election campaign. This follows our session in July providing an insight into the US election and what it could mean for Europe.

The elections will be taking place against a backdrop of seismic events in the US ‚Äì the handling of the pandemic, the economic effects and the Black Lives Matter protests, as well as issues like China, trade, etc. The campaign has been intense and divisive, between two men well into their 70s, and the result could be close. What does it mean for us in Europe? On the economy? On trade? On alliances? On support for a rules-based international system? On China and Russia? Listen back to a lively debate that will not predict the outcome, but will give a sense of the implications.

Tony Reed, EMEA Chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduces  the speakers and Matthew Kirk, International Affairs Advisor, hosts the discussion. Our panelists include:

- Former US Representative Joe Crowley, Senior Policy Advisor - former Chairman of the US House of Representatives Democratic Caucus, a senior ranking position among House Democrats
- Former US Representative Jack Kingston, Principal - former Vice-chairman of the US House of Representatives Republican Conference, a senior ranking position among House Republicans
title: What Could The US Elections Mean For Europe (15 October 2020)

description:
The latest in our series of Talk to the Experts Virtual Discussion Forums focuses on thought-leading perspectives from industry leaders and practitioners on a key Brexit challenge facing companies working in the chemicals and manufacturing industries.

The UK left the EU on 31 January 2020, and on 31 December 2020, the transitional period will come to an end, meaning that the EU REACH Regulation will no longer apply in the UK. Given the complex and cross-border nature of chemical supply chains, and the supply chain approach adopted in the REACH Regulation, this has major implications for anyone supplying chemicals into the EU or the UK from 2021, as well as those further down the supply chain who are buying and using chemicals.

In this session, our UK-based regulatory experts discuss the effect of Brexit on the REACH Regulation, both in the UK and the EU, and the key features of the new ‚ÄúUK REACH‚Äù system that is likely to apply in the UK from 2021. Whether you are a manufacturer, an importer or a distributor of chemical products, we explore the critical regulatory steps you will need to take in trading with the UK or the EU to ensure you can continue to do so, including practical examples and case studies.

Tony Reed, EMEA chair of the global Corporate Practice, introduces the following panellists:

- David Gordon, partner, Environmental, Safety & Health, Birmingham
- Anita Lloyd, director, Environmental, Safety & Health, Birmingham

Hosted by:

Matthew Kirk, international affairs advisor, London
title: Complying With REACH (8th October 2020)

description:
When you rollover a Rollover 401k into a Gold IRA, you are basically making your original 401k into a new 401k. The big difference, however, is that the entire rollover process from Rollover 401k to Gold IRA can be done online.

https://soundcloud.com/rollover401ktogoldira

Before you can rollover a Rollover 401k into a Gold IRA, you need to determine what the difference is between a Rollover 401k and a Rollover IRA. Many people think that a Rollover IRA is a certain type of Retirement account, like a Traditional IRA or a Roth IRA. This is not true.

https://soundcloud.com/rollover401ktogoldira/sets/tradinggator-rollover-401k

A Rollover IRA is a common variation of a retirement account, which is designed to take a portion of your regular income and contribute it to your retirement funds. It is one of the newer types of retirement accounts that are designed to be very flexible, so that they can be used as a source of funds for retirement purposes.

Although a Rollover IRA is a retirement plan, it is not the same as a traditional retirement plan. The traditional IRA was created by Congress, as a way for individuals to save for their future. You contribute some of your regular income into the retirement account, and you are allowed to withdraw some or all of your money at any time, without penalty.

The primary difference between a Rollover IRA and a Rollover 401k, is that the Rollover IRA does not tax your earnings. This is why it is very popular with employers. If you have any money that you earn during the year, you are able to take that money out tax-free.

A Roth IRA does not allow the same flexibility as a Rollover IRA, because the Roth IRA allows contributions to be made on a pre-tax basis. In other words, if you earn money in the regular course of your business, you are able to take that money out tax-free, and use it for your retirement.

As an example, let's say that you made a contribution to a Roth IRA and you have enough money left over, you are able to rollover that money into a Gold IRA. When you do this, you are also saving the IRS the headaches of figuring out how much income you should be putting into your retirement account, every year.

Another advantage of a Rollover 401k to a Gold IRA is that you are not locked into a certain number of dollars for years to come. You can rollover into a Rollover IRA as often as you want, as long as the money is not withdrawn from the account.

But, there is a problem with a Rollover 401k to a Gold IRA. Unlike a traditional IRA, there is no guarantee that you will get money from the Rollover IRA in future years.

And when you rollover into a Rollover IRA, you are not likely to get any of your money back. Although you are allowed to withdraw some of your money tax-free, once you have withdrawn it, you cannot get more money.

The trick is to avoid getting into a Rollover 401k to a Rollover IRA at all. You should also make sure that you are able to get a certain amount of money back, because, with a Rollover IRA, you are essentially gambling with your future income.

If you want to get the most benefit out of your Rollover 401k to a Gold IRA, then you should try to avoid getting into a Rollover 401k to a Rollover IRA. If you need to rollover the entire Rollover 401k into a Gold IRA, then you can do so at any time, but be sure to consult with a professional financial planner before you do so.

description:
Here's a quick review of how rollover IRA (RIA) annuities works. This may help clarify the IRS definition of RIA for those who are not familiar with this type of rollover arrangement.

https://soundcloud.com/rollover401ktogoldira

Rollover. In the law, the term "rollover" means the continuous transfer of assets from one account to another. In the annuity world, the term "roll" means transferring your stock or bond funds from your non-deductible taxable account to a rollover account (often called "rolling"rollover") in which you can include qualified RIA income.

https://soundcloud.com/rollover401ktogoldira/sets/tradinggator-rollover-401k

Old assets. In the case of an annuity, your "old assets" are anything that is not protected by tax shelters such as rental losses, losses from short sales, and tax-deferred withdrawals. These types of losses cannot be deducted or depreciated.

Assets included in your account. These are typically the funds in your annuity plan's account, excluding the rollover account.

Protection. The "protection" in an annuity is the tax deferral. And you can also have a rollover that provides tax protection. There are typically both federal and state tax deferred portions of the annuity rollover.

Roll over the minimum required amount. Many annuities provide a certain minimum amount of investment protection before they must be rolled over. In addition, the annuity must be purchased and closed in the account before it can be rolled over.

Investment protection. The original funds in the annuity should not be withdrawn until the proceeds are used. Withdrawals can occur at any time, but only if you are covered by the withdrawal protection provided by the original product.

Tax deferral. Usually, the annuity will provide either federal or state tax deferred portions of the rollover. If these portions of the rollover do not qualify for tax deferral, a separate rollover IRA (RIA) is provided.

Because of this important distinction, there are several types of annuities. There are also some very specific differences between these. It is best to consult with an experienced investor, such as an IRA custodian, if you have questions regarding any of the types of annuities discussed here.

It is important to understand that a Roth IRA is different from a rollover IRA. When you roll over your non-deductible IRA to a Roth IRA, you are not making a nondeductible contribution to a Roth IRA. You are instead making a nondeductible contribution to your traditional IRA. And you must take and pay taxes on your contribution before you can take your distributions from your traditional IRA.

The basic difference between the two types of rollovers is that a rollover is a name for an already-established arrangement where the IRS allows individuals to convert their entire portfolio into one type of traditional IRA. A Roth IRA, on the other hand, is a new type of retirement account, which has only recently been created and will not allow participants to convert their entire portfolios into it. It is also a relatively new form of retirement account, so people who have substantial amounts of investments in it are more likely to require a Roth IRA custodian.

While the terminology is slightly different, the basic terms and structure of a rollover IRA are very similar to a Roth IRA. Generally, a rollover takes place when the remaining balance of a non-deductible IRA is transferred to a Roth IRA. The income tax deferred portion of the Roth IRA is also usually taken as income tax deferred contributions to the traditional IRA.

A rollover from a pension into a retirement plan is a great way to save money on your money for retirement. There are many benefits to a 401k rollover. Here are just a few of them.

In a pension plan, you make contributions to your savings account and receive a certain amount of money each month. If you decide to change jobs or retire early, your contributions are still going to the pension plan. That's why it's so important to make sure your pension has a dependable provider.

https://soundcloud.com/rollover401ktogoldira/sets/tradinggator-rollover-401k

Many people choose to move their pension into an IRA or 401k because they're sure that it will be able to provide a bigger retirement nest egg for them. They also want to save on taxes. Another important benefit is that they can invest their pension money as well as their own money.

If you're already retired or thinking about retiring soon, your pension may have been put in a rollover IRA. This means that it will be transferred into your new retirement plan. The first step is to open a new account. It might be a 401k or a traditional IRA.

After you've figured out which type of account you'd like to use, you need to figure out the amount of money you need to put in your retirement plan. Your new provider will give you instructions on how much you need to contribute each month.

Before you do anything else, you need to talk to your new provider and discuss your situation. Let them know what your pension is worth to you.

When you rollover 401k to a gold IRA, you make one large contribution and then the rest is paid out every month. You make smaller contributions throughout the year until your account is maxed out.

Gold IRA accounts are good for saving because they don't have fees associated with them. They are also tax free. Their benefits aren't the same as your traditional IRA.

A major advantage to saving for retirement through a 401k rollover is that your pension is insured by the government. It's a safe haven for your retirement money. It is also the safest investment option there is.

Most states in Arizona are set up so that people with pensions will be able to choose one of these accounts for you. Your tax advisor can help you figure out the right benefits for your situation.

Rollover 401k are becoming more popular because many of us want to have a good retirement. They are very easy to use, are tax free, and will give you the income you need when you retire.

So it's important to make sure you take the time to research all of your retirement and investment opportunities. If you're not sure where to start, get online and do some shopping around for a company that will match your financial needs.
